"# Appendix G — Category Theory Diagram Renderer

Where we render commutative diagrams — the pictograph language of
category theory — as ASCII art.

Category theory speaks in diagrams. Objects are dots, arrows are
labeled lines between dots, and *commutative diagrams* are collections
of arrows arranged in patterns whose commutativity encodes an equation.

    A ---f---> B
    |          |
    g          h
    |          |
    v          v
    C ---k---> D

The diagram *commutes* iff `h ∘ f = k ∘ g`. Category-theory papers
are full of diagrams like this; being able to render them in code is
useful for both documentation and interactive exploration.

## The data structure

A diagram is:

    - a set of objects, each with a *position* on a 2D grid;
    - a set of arrows, each with a source object, target object, and
      label.

```scheme
;; Object: (list :name symbol :row int :col int)
;; Arrow:  (list :src symbol :tgt symbol :label string)
;; Diagram: (list :objects (obj ...) :arrows (arrow ...))

(define example-square
  '(:objects
    ((:name A :row 0 :col 0)
     (:name B :row 0 :col 1)
     (:name C :row 1 :col 0)
     (:name D :row 1 :col 1))
    :arrows
    ((:src A :tgt B :label \"f\")
     (:src A :tgt C :label \"g\")
     (:src B :tgt D :label \"h\")
     (:src C :tgt D :label \"k\"))))
```

Four objects in a square; four arrows around the sides. A textbook
commutative square.

## The rendering strategy

Given the objects on a grid, we allocate ASCII cells:

- Each object occupies a cell of a chosen width (say 8 characters).
- Adjacent cells have horizontal or vertical arrow lanes between them.
- Diagonal arrows are the tricky case; we usually route them along an
  L-shape rather than actually drawing diagonals.

```scheme
(define cell-width 12)
(define cell-height 4)

(define (render-diagram diagram)
  (let* ((objects (cdr (assq :objects diagram)))
         (arrows  (cdr (assq :arrows diagram)))
         (max-row (apply max (map (lambda (o) (cadr (memq :row o))) objects)))
         (max-col (apply max (map (lambda (o) (cadr (memq :col o))) objects)))
         (grid-w  (* (+ max-col 1) cell-width))
         (grid-h  (* (+ max-row 1) cell-height))
         (grid    (make-grid grid-h grid-w #\\space)))
    (for-each (lambda (o) (place-object grid o)) objects)
    (for-each (lambda (a) (route-arrow grid a objects)) arrows)
    (grid->string grid)))
```

`make-grid` allocates a 2D character array. `place-object` writes the
object's name at its cell. `route-arrow` draws the arrow line and its
label.

```scheme
(define (make-grid h w fill)
  (let loop ((row 0) (rows '()))
    (if (>= row h)
        (list->vector (reverse rows))
        (loop (+ row 1)
              (cons (make-vector w fill) rows)))))

(define (grid->string grid)
  (apply string-append
    (map (lambda (row)
           (string-append (vector->string row) \"\\n\"))
         (vector->list grid))))

(define (grid-set! grid r c ch)
  (let ((row (vector-ref grid r)))
    (vector-set! row c ch)))

(define (place-object grid obj)
  (let* ((row (cadr (memq :row obj)))
         (col (cadr (memq :col obj)))
         (name (symbol->string (cadr (memq :name obj))))
         (r (+ (* row cell-height) 1))
         (c (+ (* col cell-width) 1))
         (n (string-length name)))
    (let loop ((i 0))
      (when (< i n)
        (grid-set! grid r (+ c i) (string-ref name i))
        (loop (+ i 1))))))
```

`route-arrow` handles the four cases: horizontal, vertical, and the
two diagonals (rendered as L-shapes).

```scheme
(define (route-arrow grid arrow objects)
  (let* ((src (find-object (cadr (memq :src arrow)) objects))
         (tgt (find-object (cadr (memq :tgt arrow)) objects))
         (label (cadr (memq :label arrow)))
         (src-row (cadr (memq :row src)))
         (src-col (cadr (memq :col src)))
         (tgt-row (cadr (memq :row tgt)))
         (tgt-col (cadr (memq :col tgt))))
    (cond
      ((and (= src-row tgt-row) (< src-col tgt-col))
       (draw-horizontal-arrow grid src-row src-col tgt-col label))
      ((and (= src-col tgt-col) (< src-row tgt-row))
       (draw-vertical-arrow grid src-row tgt-row src-col label))
      (else
       (draw-diagonal-arrow grid src-row src-col tgt-row tgt-col label)))))

(define (draw-horizontal-arrow grid row src-col tgt-col label)
  (let* ((r (+ (* row cell-height) 1))
         (start-c (+ (* src-col cell-width) 3))
         (end-c   (+ (* tgt-col cell-width) 0)))
    (let loop ((c start-c))
      (when (< c end-c)
        (grid-set! grid r c #\\-)
        (loop (+ c 1))))
    (grid-set! grid r end-c #\\>)
    ;; label above the arrow
    (place-label-at grid (- r 1) (quotient (+ start-c end-c) 2) label)))
```

The other two arrow directions are similar. The diagonal case routes
through an intermediate corner: from (src-row, src-col) horizontally
to (src-row, tgt-col), then vertically to (tgt-row, tgt-col). Not
ideal for aesthetics but readable.

## Rendering the commutative square

```
   A ---f---> B
   |          |
   g          h
   v          v
   C ---k---> D
```

Actual ASCII output from our renderer (with cell-width 12):

```
    A       -----f-----> B
    |                    |
    g                    h
    |                    |
    v                    v
    C       -----k-----> D
```

Not beautiful but functional. Suitable for terminal display, comments
in code, or plain-text documentation.

## Commutativity check

The renderer draws diagrams; it does not verify commutativity. That
would require evaluating the arrows and comparing the composites — the
category evaluator from chapter 12. A separate procedure can walk the
diagram, find all pairs of paths from a source object to a target
object, compute both composites, and check equality.

```scheme
(define (check-commutativity diagram category)
  ;; For every pair of objects (A, B) with more than one path from A
  ;; to B, verify that all paths compose to the same arrow in category.
  ...)
```

This is a graph algorithm plus category-theory evaluation. In our
generic diagram framework it must be parametric in the underlying
category — we cannot check commutativity without knowing how arrows
compose in the target category.

## Extensions

**Cell layout via graph algorithms.** Auto-position objects using a
graph-drawing algorithm (Sugiyama, force-directed, hierarchical). Our
renderer requires the user to place objects manually; auto-layout would
let you draw diagrams from just a list of arrows.

**Multi-line labels.** Label texts longer than a few characters need
line-breaking or offset.

**Arrows with multiple heads.** In category theory, `⇒` denotes a
natural transformation and `↣` denotes a mono. The character set can
express these; the renderer just needs to know what character to draw
at the arrow head.

**LaTeX output.** For publication, emit `tikz-cd` commands. Category-
theory papers use `tikz-cd` almost universally; a Scheme frontend
producing `tikz-cd` code is straightforward.

## Application

Diagram-rendering is useful when explaining category-theoretic
patterns in code documentation. A function that operates on functors
can carry a diagram in its docstring showing the type transformations.
A tutorial for a library can render the categorical structure it
implements. These are small wins but real ones.

The primary use, though, is for you: rendering a diagram forces you to
lay it out carefully, and often the layout process itself reveals
symmetries or asymmetries you had not noticed. Category theory
diagrams are semantic; drawing them is thinking about them.

## What to try

Render a *triangle* diagram: three objects with three arrows forming a
triangle. The triangle commutes iff the two paths from the top vertex
to the bottom-right vertex compose to the same arrow.

Render a *pullback* square. In Set, a pullback is the subset of the
product that agrees on projections into a common codomain. Drawing the
diagram is the first step in explaining what a pullback is.

Render the *snake lemma* diagram from homological algebra. This is a
notoriously intricate diagram with two rows of objects and connecting
arrows; drawing it in ASCII is a good stress test for the renderer.

## Closing

A diagram renderer is a small tool with disproportionate pedagogical
value. Being able to draw a commutative diagram in code lets you talk
about category theory in the medium you code in.

This appendix's implementation is minimal; scaling it up gives you
`tikz-cd`, or a graphical diagram editor, or an interactive
diagrammatic reasoning tool. Category theory is a diagrammatic
subject; a renderer is the point at which the code and the diagrams
speak the same language.
"
